<div class="col clear facility">
<div class="col three-sm">
<h3 id="FacilityGroupProxy38812ac03cfb4f2ba06c302e810ef43e-4">Counselling and Support</h3>
<ul class="facility-list clear">
<li class="not-answered">Bereavement support <span>(not answered)</span></li>
<li class="no">Translation services<span class="hidden"> (no)</span></li>
</ul>
<div id="imageContent1e6567fc2938409581396b5d8ee54b6f">
</div>
<p>Counselling and SupportSupport is available for patients and families from the Bereavement Office and from the Patient Advice and Liaison Service (PALS).PALS provides an independent service, which is easily accessible to patients, their carers and their families to help resolve their concerns quickly and efficiently, where necessary speaking on the clients behalf or referring them to the appropriate staff. PALS can provide information and support to patients to help make their contact with the NHS as easy as possible.To contact PALS Tel: 0800 019 3282 Fax: 08454 226832Email: pals.gloucestershirehospitals@glos.nhs.ukText: 07827 281266The Bereavement Office provides support and advice to close relatives or next of kin when someone dies in hospital.The Bereavement Office is given details of the death and any remaining property  belonging to the deceased person may be taken to the office or kept on the ward for relatives to collect. They will arrange for the Medical Certificate of cause of death to be signed and issued by the Doctor as soon as possible. The Bereavement Officer will advise when the certificate is ready and will arrange a mutually convenient time for family members or next of kin to collect this and any personal possessions. They may be asked whether the deceased person is to receive a cremation or a burial. In the case of cremation extra forms are required which the Funeral Director will arrange to collect from the hospital after the Medical Staff have completed them.The Bereavement Officer also provides help and support in relation to visiting the deceased, registering the death, post mortems (where required), inquests, organ and tissue retention, organ donation, funerals and probate. There is a useful and comprehensive booklet provided which covers all of these areas which is given to all families or next of kin when someone dies in hospital.To contact the Bereavement Office at Gloucestershire Royal Hospital Telephone: 08454 226742 (Monday to Friday, 10am - 4pm. Sometimes there will be an answer phone, please do leave a message and it will be returned as soon as possible).Support on discharge from hospital is available, particularly for those patients who cannot return to their own homes, and for their families.There is  a sudden unexpected death counselling service available within the Emergency Department ( formerly known as A&amp;E).</p>
</div>
